
English:Experiment 2: Bright-Dark Fringe Regulation Experiment by Adding Magnifier in Double-Slit Optical Path
1. Experimental Purpose
This experiment verifies that the dark fringes of double-slit diffraction are not fixed results formed by wave interference and cancellation as claimed by traditional theories, but temporary distributions produced by the dense or sparse arrangement of propagating particles. By precisely controlling the distance of the magnifying glass, dark fringes can be weakened and eliminated, directly revealing the core contradictions of the traditional optical interference theory.
2. Experimental Equipment
Monochromatic parallel light source, standard double-slit diffraction plate, magnifying glass (convex lens), receiving light screen, optical fixing bracket
3. Experimental Procedures
Build the basic double-slit optical path: fix the parallel light source, double-slit diffraction plate and receiving light screen in sequence with coaxial alignment. Turn on the light source to form stable, well-defined alternating bright and dark double-slit fringes on the screen.
Place the magnifying glass in the middle section of the optical path between the double-slit plate and the light screen, and fix the lens with a bracket without changing the original positions of the light source, double slit and light screen.
Adjust the axial distance of the magnifying glass slowly and accurately while avoiding invalid ranges. Moving too far from the double slit or too close to the screen cannot produce the expected effect; it is necessary to adjust to the optimal middle position matching the focal length of the lens.
Keep the optical path stable, observe and record the morphological changes of bright and dark fringes on the screen.
4. Expected Experimental Phenomena
Without the magnifying glass, alternating bright and dark fringes appear on the screen with clear boundaries and zero brightness in dark areas.
When the magnifying glass is adjusted to the accurate effective distance, the original distinct dark fringes gradually fade and eventually disappear completely. Only a light spot with continuous and gentle brightness gradient remains, without segmented dark areas or regular interference fringes.
5. Core Experimental Conclusions
Traditional theories claim that dark fringes are generated by the cancellation of wave crests and troughs, which is regarded as a fixed physical effect. Since magnifiers cannot change the essence of wave interference, dark fringes should not disappear. This inference is completely inconsistent with the experimental phenomena.
This experiment confirms that the essence of double-slit bright and dark fringes lies in the density difference of particle propagation restricted by double-slit boundaries. By adjusting the propagation angle of particles and breaking up local dense gathering states, the magnifying glass can directly eliminate dark fringes, and all phenomena can be explained without the theory of wave interference and energy cancellation.
The key control variable is the relative distance between the magnifying glass and the optical path. Only precise adjustment within the effective range can trigger the reduction or disappearance of dark fringes. It further proves that the light and dark distribution is a manually adjustable result of particle arrangement, rather than an immutable wave interference effect.
